Recommendation
We recommended, and Management agreed to the following:
The Inventory Committee conducts the physical inventory count for all PPE items once a year, as at December 31 of each year;
The Municipal Accountant coordinate with the appropriate LGU official or personnel concerning the status of the Road Concreting Project recorded under the Road Network account in the Trust Fund books and make appropriate adjustment as necessary;
The Municipal Accountant and the GSO reconcile their PPE records in order to reflect a correct and accurate balances in the FS;
The Municipal Accountant provide sufficient disclosure on missing items still recorded in the books of the LGU and coordinate with the General Services Office (GSO) on the status of these missing items for possible reversal of the same subject to applicable rules and regulation on the write-off of PPE accounts;
The Municipal Accountant verify the correctness of the Watercraft account with a negative carrying amount and make appropriate adjustment as necessary; and
Conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE balances in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 in order to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability.

Recommendation
We recommended, and management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant review corresponding records to check that the inventory balances as reflected in the FS are reconciled with the supporting ledgers or records;
The accounting and the GSO ensure that inventory records such as the Supply Ledger Card, SPLC, Stock Card, SPC and RegSPI, whichever is applicable, are properly maintained and updated regularly for all items of inventory;
The accounting and the GSO reconcile their records in order to provide accurate inventory balances at reporting dates;
The GSO prepares and submits to the accounting office the SSMI/RSPI together with the original copy of the RIS on a weekly basis;
The accounting unit record the issuance of inventory items based on the SSMI/RSPI submitted by the general services office; and
The Inventory Committee conducts the physical inventory count of inventories twice a year, as at June 30 and as at December 31 of each year and submit the RPCI as follows:
Original copy		- Accounting Unit
Duplicate copy		- COA Auditor
Triplicate copy		- Supply and Property Unit
Quadruplicate copy		- Inventory Committee file

Recommendation
We recommended the following:
The Municipal Accountant verify the validity of all recorded payables and make confirmations to check whether said claims actually exist or not especially those which are long outstanding and consider the reversion of those payables with no actual claimant;
The Municipal Engineer coordinate with the Municipal Accountant and the Local Chief Executive regarding the status of the Consultancy Services for the preparation of Detailed Engineering Design (DED) of the Two-Storey GAD building to determine whether said obligation still exist or subject for cancellation and to discuss further appropriate action such as reversal of the payable account or settlement through payment;
Payments of all payables with valid claimants and complete supporting documents, subject to possible liquidated damages, if any, be immediately made or processed in accordance with the applicable rules and regulations and upon the presumption that budgets for these obligations were already earmarked through the Obligation Request duly signed by the budget officer to avoid accumulation of unpaid obligations;
The Municipal Accountant ensures that all payables recorded in the books of the LGU are adequately supported with necessary documents;
The accounting office monitors the status of all disbursement vouchers released by them after checking the completeness of its supporting documents to check whether payment has already been made or not; and
The Municipal Accountant effects the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify the accounts erroneously booked in the Accounts Payable account to ensure that accounts are accurately presented in the financial statements.

Recommendation
We recommended the following:
The Municipal Accountant inform the Municipal Treasurer in writing about the stale check noted in the BRS;
The Municipal Treasurer determine the status of the Stale Check and prepare a report showing as to whether this check was already claimed by the payee or still unreleased and on hand;
The Municipal Treasurer send communication to the concerned payee informing the latter on the status of the check. If the concerned payee appeared to claim the check or requested for a re-issuance of the stale check, the Municipal Treasurer issue a new check to the claimant in accordance with the procedures provided under Section 59 of COA Circular No. 2002-003 on Spoiled and Stale Checks; and
After exhaustion of the communication phase and the check still remained unclaimed in the possession of the Municipal Treasurer, the latter submit the necessary documents to the Municipal Accountant for the recording of the corresponding payable.

We recommended to the GSO the following:
Institute a more systematic filing of OR/CR records for easier identification, monitoring and retrieval of the same;
Locate the OR/CRs of the motor vehicles that have no existing OR/CRs in file. If warranted, Management coordinate with the LTO for the issuance of a duplicate OR/CR of the vehicle;
Cause the transfer of vehicle registration of the five units to the Municipal Government of Molave;
Cause the updating of the registration payments of expired vehicle registrations and ensure annual compliance thereof;
Furthermore, penalties arising from the late registration be charged to the person responsible for the registration and not against LGU Funds;
Implement the use of Temporary License Plates for all vehicles in accordance with the specifications laid out under the 2017 LTO Memorandum;
Require the reinstallation of the side mirrors on all motorcycle units; and
All the vehicles be plainly marked “For Official Use Only” and also the name of the department/office such vehicle/s has been issued be indicated to properly identify responsibility on the vehicles used. Furthermore, only the corresponding fuel consumed by vehicles with the required markings will only be allowed in audit.

We recommended the following:
Instruct the BAC and Municipal Engineer to properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave the way for their timely implementation and completion;
Ensure that the MPDC regularly monitor the status of project implementation so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time;
Conduct intensive review of the continuing projects funded under the 20% DF to determine if the PPAs are still part of the vital needs of the Municipality, otherwise, reprogram the identified PPAs to priority PPAs; and,
Realign or reprogram the unutilized/unimplemented PPAs identified to Priority Development PPAs in accordance with the DBM and DILG JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017.

We reiterate our recommendations as follows:
The Inventory Committee conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality and render a Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;
The General Services Officer:
Render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map;
Regularly maintain and update the Registry of Public Infrastructures for Roads; and
